{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Migrations are applied in ascending numeric order determined by the filename prefix.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure boundary is the handoff between file discovery/parsing and execution sequencing. A pure unit sort test can miss real wiring bugs (e.g., discovery order leaking through, wrong parsed prefix passed to executor). No real subprocess or external network is required, and no LLM dependency exists.","test_description":"Run the runner against a temp `migrations/` directory with out-of-order filenames (e.g., `010_...sql`, `002_...sql`, `001_...sql`) and a local test DB table that records execution order. Assert rows prove execution order `001,002,010`.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.3,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.005,"Workflow":0.005}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"A migration that has already been applied is not re-executed on a subsequent run.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This behavior depends on persisted state across runs (`_migrations` table) and module interaction between planner and metadata reads/writes. Unit tests of one function can miss re-execution caused by SQL/state wiring. No subprocess requirement, no LLM dependency.","test_description":"Use a local test DB. Run runner once with a migration that inserts a sentinel row. Run runner again. Assert sentinel appears once and `_migrations` has one record for that migration.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.82,"System":0.07,"Agentic":0.005,"Workflow":0.005}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When a migration statement fails, its changes are rolled back automatically and no further migrations in the same run are attempted.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Real failure is transactional behavior plus control-flow stop-on-error across modules. Mock DBs often hide rollback semantics, so a real local DB transaction is needed. Still does not require subprocess orchestration or any AI model.","test_description":"With a local test DB, provide migration A (valid partial write + then failing statement) and migration B (valid). Run runner and expect failure. Assert no partial changes from A are committed, B was not applied, and `_migrations` has no entry for failed/blocked migrations.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.87,"System":0.09,"Agentic":0.005,"Workflow":0.005}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"When two instances of the runner start at the same time against the same database, each migration is applied exactly once across both instances.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"The behavior explicitly depends on concurrent separate processes and timing/locking behavior. That is beyond single-process integration and requires subprocess-level execution to expose race conditions. Mocking or single-process simulation can falsely pass.","test_description":"Launch two runner processes simultaneously against the same local PostgreSQL instance and same migration set. After both exit, assert each migration effect appears exactly once and `_migrations` contains one record per migration (no duplicates, no misses).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.0,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.91,"Agentic":0.005,"Workflow":0.005}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"On the very first run against a fresh database, the `_migrations` table is created before any migration file is applied.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is bootstrap ordering across runner initialization and migration execution modules with real DB schema state. Unit tests can miss SQL/bootstrap wiring defects. No subprocess or AI dependency required.","test_description":"Against a brand-new local test DB, run with a migration that succeeds only if `_migrations` already exists (or inspect schema immediately after bootstrap hook). Assert `_migrations` is created and first migration is then applied successfully.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.08,"Integration":0.84,"System":0.07,"Agentic":0.005,"Workflow":0.005}}]}
